HSBC, PetroChina, Tiger Airways: Asia Ex-Japan Equity Preview

-- B y   B e r n i   M o e s t a f a
-- 
2011-05-19T21:55:21Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-19/hsbc-petrochina-tiger-airways-asia-ex-japan-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
unusual price changes today in Asian trading, excluding  Japan .
Stock symbols are in parentheses, and share prices are from the
previous close, unless noted otherwise.  Aboitiz Power Corp. (AP)  : The Philippine energy
company’s stock rating was raised to “buy” from “hold” with
a 12-month share-price target at 36.35 pesos by Laura Dy-Liacco,
an analyst at ATR KimEng Securities Inc. The stock fell 0.5
percent to 29.75 pesos.  Cebu Air Inc. (CEB)  : The Philippines’ Civil Aeronautics
Board issued a provisional order stopping Tiger Airways Holdings
Ltd. from “implementing its marketing arrangement” with local
carrier South East Asian Airlines for the Manila to Cebu and
Manila to Davao flights using aircraft leased from Tiger. The
order “is based on strong indications of possible violation of
the restriction on cabotage,” Executive Director Carmelo
Arcilla said in a mobile phone message yesterday to Bloomberg
News.  Cebu Air, which competes with South East Asian Air, rose
0.5 percent to 96 pesos.  Geely Automobile Holdings Ltd. (175)  (175 HK): The automaker
whose parent bought Volvo Cars said curbs on power demand
imposed by the eastern Chinese province of Zhejiang won’t be
“much of a problem.” Geely’s factories are in Taizhou and
Ningbo cities, which have been less seriously affected than
bigger cities such as Hangzhou, Zhang Xiaodong, a spokesman for
Zhejiang Geely said by phone. Geely slid 0.3 percent to HK$3.19.  Green Energy Technology Inc. (3519)  (3519 TT): The company’s board
approved plans to enter into a five-year syndicated loan of no
more than $84 million to fund equipment for ingot and wafer
production, Taipei-based Green Energy said in an e-mailed
statement. Green Energy, which makes solar components, fell 0.5
percent to NT$102.50.  HSBC Holdings Plc (5)  (5 HK):  Europe ’s largest bank by market
value sees a “quite high” chance to be a yuan clearing bank in
 Hong Kong  if rules allow, said Peter Wong, the bank’s chief
executive officer for the Asia-Pacific region. HSBC fell 0.3
percent to HK$80.55.  PetroChina Co. (857 HK): The nation’s second-biggest
refiner will shut half the capacity of its largest refining
plant in northern  China ’s Dalian city for more than a month for
maintenance, said a company official, who declined to be
identified because of company rules. PetroChina climbed 0.6
percent to HK$10.64.  PT Telekomunikasi Indonesia (TLKM IJ): Shareholders of
Indonesia’s biggest telephone operator approved a plan to buy
back up to 3.2 percent of the company or about 645 million
shares from the market, President Director Rinaldi Firmansyah
said. Telekomunikasi plans to buy the shares for 7,750 rupiah
each or as much as 5 trillion rupiah ($584.6 million) over an
18-month period starting May 20, he said in Jakarta. Telkom, as
the company is also known, fell 1.9 percent to 7,600 rupiah.  Tiger Airways Holdings Ltd. (TGR)  : The discount carrier
part-owned by Singapore Airlines Ltd. said fourth-quarter net
income was S$1.3 million ($1.1 million), compared with S$22.3
million a year earlier. Tiger Airways climbed 0.7 percent to
S$1.55.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Berni Moestafa in Jakarta at 
